ecession. However, it is said that Presi\ndent Truman is not inclined to use such a\nprogram to bolster up our economy. The\nPresident'* Economic Advisory Council\nquestions the efficacy of a public works\n\u2022f' gram at this time. When the council\nuakei its report on July 1, it may advocate\nother means to increase employment.\n*'*d to revive buying of the nation\u2019s vast\nu i\u2019put of manufactured articles.*''\nBut the nation, as a whole, is far bet\nter off than it was after the Stock Market\ncroak in November, 1929. T>day the sav\ning* of Americans are many times greater\ntkaa they were 20 years ago. The pifblic\nk* money with which to buy but it has set\nup and is maintaining buyers\u2019 resistence\nhtcauae of high prices.\nPrices are grodually coming down but\ntke cuts are not sufficiently large to make\ntka public open its pocketbook. For in\nstance, recently an automobile manufac\nttoftor announced that the prices of one line\naf its cars had been reduced sls, which\nfails far short of being an incentive to\nanybody who is waiting to purchase anew\ncar when prices are \u201creasonable.\u201d It is im\npossible to determine the mass psychology\non what is considered \u201creasonable,\u201d\nthough, as if actuated by the same impulse,\nthe time will come when the public will\nrespond to inducements to buy.\nMeanwhile, you may be able to sit by\ncontentedly till prices suit you for the\ntypes of manufactured goods you wish to\nbuy, provided you took The Citizen's ad\nvice to save when times were better than\ngood.\nA government, administered for the\ngood of all citizens, should recognize no\nprivileged class.\nMass demonstrations for political pur\npose* is one European custom that seems\nto be growing in the United States.\nThe Russians have a host of friends in\nthe United States, including the business\nman who does nothing but grab a profit.\nNO VOTE LITTLE INTEREST\nThe plight of Palestinian Arab refu\ngees is becoming serious' because funds\nare not available to suply these victims\nof warfare with adequate food.\nThe number of refugees is estimated\nto be about one million. The Internation\nal Red Cross reports 490,000 refugees in\nEastern Palestine, the League of Red Cross\nSocieties in Lebanon, Syria and Jordan\nreports 333,000 and the Quakers in the\nGaza strip report 270,000. In addition, the\nQuakers report a resident civilian popu\nlation in their area, about 80,000 in num\nber, \u201cpractically as destitute as the refu\ngees.\u201d\nThe plight of these victims of the\nfight in Palestine has not received fhe sym\npathetic consideration of the people of\nthe United States. The principles of hu\nmanity, so blatantly proclaimed in the\ninterest of the displaced persons of Eu\nrope, have not been called to mind for\nthe benefit of the Arab regugees. This is\npassing strange, if, in reality,, the hue\nand cry made in behalf of the European\nrefugees was based upon humanitarian\nmotives.\nThe cynical suggest that the Arabs\nwould fare better if there were, in the\nUnited States several million persons of\nArabic descent, ready and able to vote\nin our elections. Those running for of\nfice, where the Arabs happened to pos\nse** political strength, would be \u201ccon\ni cerned\u201d about the Arabic refugees and\nprobably would make a trip by plane to\nthe area in order to acquaint themselves\nwith tke needs of the Arabs.\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nChinese Banker Studies American\nBankinagSystem of Registering\nAnd Sling U. S. Saving Bonds\nr fipffiHfM* r i\"-\nfSfl\nI t\nI! 1\n(LEFT TO RIGHTJ Miss Clarice Hsi of Shanghai. Chipa. and.\nSavings Roads Department Manager. First Wisconsin Rational\nBank. Milwaukee. Wisconsin. Harry Kaiser.\nFortune In\nOld House\nCHICAGO.\u2014After her father\u2019s\ndeath, Mrs; Lucille Sehader went\nto Doquoin to \u2018\u2018tidy\u201d *up the\nhouse before renting it She\nfound a jar containing \u201cbuttons\u201d,\nand threw it out without exam\nination. Neighbors noticed the